}
{{ machine_class_name(model) }}_destroy(machine);
```

### Single-command C Builds

The examples below are validated with gcc / clang style command lines.
Compile the generated runtime and your application together:

```bash
cc -std=c99 -Wall -Wextra -pedantic -O2 machine.c app.c -lm -o app
```

Equivalent explicit gcc / clang forms are:

```bash
gcc -std=c99 -Wall -Wextra -pedantic -O2 machine.c app.c -lm -o app
clang -std=c99 -Wall -Wextra -pedantic -O2 machine.c app.c -lm -o app
```

For a no-heap build, define the same profile symbol for the generated runtime
and every consumer that includes `machine.h`:

```bash
cc -std=c99 -DPYFCSTM_GENERATED_NO_HEAP -Wall -Wextra -pedantic -O2 machine.c app.c -lm -o app
```

A separate object build is also valid:

```bash
cc -std=c99 -Wall -Wextra -c machine.c -o machine.o
cc -std=c99 -Wall -Wextra -c app.c -o app.o
cc machine.o app.o -lm -o app
```

On Windows, use the equivalent library or DLL flags for your compiler toolchain
and do not force-link the POSIX math library `m`.

### CMake Integration

A minimal static-library integration can look like this:

```cmake
cmake_minimum_required(VERSION 3.5)
project(generated_machine_app C)

add_library(machine STATIC machine.c)
target_include_directories(machine PUBLIC ${CMAKE_CURRENT_SOURCE_DIR})
set_target_properties(
    machine
    PROPERTIES
    C_STANDARD 99
    C_STANDARD_REQUIRED YES
    C_EXTENSIONS NO
)

if(NOT WIN32)
    target_link_libraries(machine PUBLIC m)
endif()

add_executable(app app.c)
target_link_libraries(app PRIVATE machine)
```

For a no-heap library that is consumed by other targets, propagate the macro as
part of the public interface:

```cmake
target_compile_definitions(machine PUBLIC PYFCSTM_GENERATED_NO_HEAP)
```

If `machine.c` is compiled into an interface-style wrapper, use
`INTERFACE PYFCSTM_GENERATED_NO_HEAP` on the wrapper target. A `PRIVATE`
definition is only safe when `machine.c` and all consumer source files that
include `machine.h` are compiled in the same final target and therefore see the
same macro.

### C++ Compile Checking

Compile checking with a C++ compiler is also supported and recommended when
your integration layer is C++:

```bash
g++ -x c++ -std=c++98 -Wall -Wextra -Werror -pedantic-errors -c machine.c -o machine.o
g++ -x c++ -std=c++17 -Wall -Wextra -Werror -pedantic-errors -c machine.c -o machine.o
```


### Native Toolchain Evidence

The repository-level native toolchain matrix builds representative generated
`c` and `c_poll` artifacts through pytest with the same shared semantic fixture
corpus used by the simulator and template-alignment tests. Public profiles cover
hosted GCC / Clang optimization levels, 32-bit Linux, AArch64 with QEMU,
AppleClang, Windows MinGW / MSVC / clang-cl, sanitizer runs, compile-only ARM
bare-metal checks, and report-only static analysis such as `cppcheck` and
`clang-tidy`.

Those profiles are an engineering compatibility baseline, not a certification
claim. Treat them as reproducible evidence that the generated public API and
shared semantics survive common compiler families and build modes. Safety
standards, coding-rule sign-off, board support packages, linker scripts, and
project-specific warning policies remain the responsibility of the downstream
integration process.

When a native matrix job fails, inspect the uploaded `result.json`,
`commands.json`, command logs, generated files, and harness files. Runnable
profiles also include `observations.jsonl`; compile-only and analyze-only
profiles intentionally do not produce runtime observations.

### Boundary Notes

- The no-heap profile only removes generated heap allocation helpers. It is not
  a strict freestanding guarantee; the generated runtime may still use standard
  headers such as `<math.h>`, `<string.h>`, or `<stdio.h>`.
- This generated runtime is not a claim of MISRA, AUTOSAR, DO-178C, IEC 61508,
  or ISO 26262 certification readiness.
- Binary layout, endian conversion, and cross-device persistence of variable
  snapshots are outside this public contract.

### Integration Preflight Checklist

Before integrating this generated runtime into controller, firmware, or hardware
adapter code, confirm the following points in the downstream project:

- Compile the C core as C99 and choose one memory profile: default hosted,
  caller-owned object, or `PYFCSTM_GENERATED_NO_HEAP`. The no-heap profile only
  removes generated allocation helpers; it is not a full freestanding or safety
  certification profile.
- Install every abstract hook that the application depends on. Hooks are
  read-only extension points; do not mutate generated persistent variables from
  hook callbacks.
- Submit generated integer event ids through `{{ machine_class_name(model) }}_cycle(...)`; do
  not reintroduce runtime string event lookup in application glue.
- Treat one `{{ machine_class_name(model) }}` instance as non-reentrant. Serialize
  `init`, `hot_start`, `cycle`, hook registration, and state/variable reads when
  ISR, scheduler, or multi-threaded code can touch the same instance.
- Keep volatile registers, DMA buffers, communication frames, and device I/O in
  an outer adapter. Do not model them as generated persistent variables merely
  to access hardware directly; bridge them through event submission, hooks, or
  application-owned adapter code.
- Run `pyfcstm inspect` before C/C++ deployment and review numeric warnings.
  Those diagnostics describe default C/C++ deployment-profile risks; Python
  generated runtimes have different numeric and exception behavior. Follow-up
  BitVec / BMC / fixed-point proof work is tracked in
  <https://github.com/HansBug/pyfcstm/issues/254>, and future codegen numeric
  strategy work is tracked in <https://github.com/HansBug/pyfcstm/issues/255>.
- Treat native toolchain matrix results, sanitizer runs, `cppcheck`, and
  `clang-tidy` as engineering evidence only. They do not make this generated
  runtime MISRA, AUTOSAR, DO-178C, IEC 61508, ISO 26262, or other certification
  ready by themselves.

### Linkage and Visibility

- `{{ machine_macro_name(model) }}_API` is the generated symbol-visibility macro
  used by all public functions.
- Define `{{ machine_macro_name(model) }}_BUILD_SHARED` when building the
  generated runtime itself as a Windows DLL.
- Define `{{ machine_macro_name(model) }}_USE_SHARED` when consuming that DLL
  from external code on Windows.
- `machine.h` wraps only the public API declarations in `extern "C"` when
  included from C++.
- Public layout structs and hook typedefs stay usable from both C and C++.
- In generated integer fields, `{{ machine_class_name(model) }}Int` is the
  public signed 64-bit type alias chosen to stay valid in both C99 and C++98+.

