### Function Usage Notes

- `{{ machine_class_name(model) }}_create()` / `{{ machine_class_name(model) }}_destroy()`:
  use these if you want heap allocation managed by the generated runtime. They
  belong to the default hosted profile; in the no-heap profile, allocate the
  machine object yourself and call `{{ machine_class_name(model) }}_init()` or
  `{{ machine_class_name(model) }}_hot_start(...)`.
- `{{ machine_class_name(model) }}_init()`:
  use this for stack-allocated machines or to reset an existing machine.
- `{{ machine_class_name(model) }}_hot_start()`:
  `initial_vars` must describe a complete persistent-state snapshot compatible
  with `initial_state_id`.
- `{{ machine_class_name(model) }}_cycle()`:
  pass `NULL` and `0u` when a cycle should run without external events.
- `{{ machine_class_name(model) }}_vars()`:
  returns a read-only pointer; if you need a mutable external snapshot, copy the
  struct value out first.
- `{{ machine_class_name(model) }}_last_error()`:
  useful after any API call that returned `{{ machine_macro_name(model) }}_FAILURE`.
- `{{ machine_class_name(model) }}_dsl_source()`:
  useful for diagnostics, traceability, or exposing the canonical / normalized
  model export to tooling.

