## Performance Advice

- Use the generated event-id macros directly; do not reintroduce runtime string
  parsing in your application layer.
- Reuse `static const {{ machine_class_name(model) }}EventId[]` arrays for hot
  event paths instead of rebuilding temporary arrays every cycle.
- Pass `NULL, 0u` for no-event cycles instead of creating an empty array.
- Keep hook registration sparse on critical paths; installed hooks introduce
  extra callback overhead.
- Treat the generated runtime as reusable stateful infrastructure: initialize
  once, cycle many times, and avoid unnecessary create/destroy churn.
- Build production binaries with optimization enabled, for example `-O2` or
  `-O3`, and usually `-DNDEBUG`.
- If your toolchain supports it and your build policy allows it, LTO can help
  further: for example `-flto`.
- Prefer hot start when restoring from a known checkpoint, because it avoids
  reconstructing that checkpoint externally through many normal cycles.
- Do not mutate runtime-owned internal fields such as `stack`, `stack_size`,
  `hooks`, or `last_error` directly; use the public APIs instead so the runtime
  can preserve its optimized invariants.

## Compatibility Notes

- The generated runtime targets C99 and C++98 or later.
- Template regression checks compile representative generated machines with both
  a C compiler and a C++ compiler.
- Template regression checks also run representative C++ harnesses covering
  basic behavior, hot start, rollback behavior, keyword-safe identifiers, and
  abstract hook mounting.
